The data were collected to show have active residents are with nearby water resources, said Kimberly Williams, Environment Maryland spokeswoman. 
She was joined by Maryland State Park Ranger Steve McCoy, who oversees Sandy Point State Park. 
"We are truly a gateway to all the bay has to offer," McCoy said during the event. "If the water quality of the bay declines, not only does the associated habitat — the native flora and fauna — suffer, but countless families that enjoy the natural beauty, fun and adventure in this great resource could be robbed of that connection."
